{{Infobox operational plan | name = Italian military intervention in Spain | partof = the [[Spanish Civil War]] | image = S25.jpeg | caption = Republican poster, reading "The claw of the Italian invader intends to enslave us." | scope = | type = | location = [[Spain]] | coordinates = | map_type = | latitude = | longitude = | map_size = | map_caption = | map_label = | planned = | planned_by = | objective = Assist [[National faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalist forces]] | target = | date = 1936–39 | time = | time-begin = | time-end = | timezone = | executed_by = {{flag|Fascist Italy (1922–1943)|name=Italy}} *[[Aviazione Legionaria]] *[[Corpo Truppe Volontarie]] *[[Italian Royal Navy]] | outcome = Successful operation: * [[Second Spanish Republic]] defeated * Establishment of [[Francisco Franco]]'s regime | casualties = | fatalities = | injuries = }} The '''Italian military intervention in Spain''' took place during the [[Spanish Civil War]] in order to support the nationalist cause against the [[Second Spanish Republic]]. As the conquest of Ethiopia in the [[Second Italo-Abyssinian War]] made Italy confident in its power, Benito Mussolini joined the war to secure Fascist control of the [[Mediterranean]].<ref>Beevor (2006). pp. 135–6.</ref> The [[Regia Marina|Royal Italian Navy]] ({{lang-it|Regia Marina|italic=no}}) played a substantial role in the Mediterranean blockade, and ultimately Italy supplied machine guns, artillery, aircraft, [[tankette]]s, the [[Aviazione Legionaria]], and the [[Corpo Truppe Volontarie]] (CTV) to the Nationalist cause.<ref name="Beevor 2006. p. 199">Beevor (2006). p. 199.</ref> The Italian CTV would, at its peak, supply the Nationalists with 70,000 men.<ref name="Beevor 2006. p. 199" /> Italian warships took part in breaking the Republican navy's [[blockade]] of Nationalist-held Spanish Morocco and took part in naval bombardment of Republican-held Málaga, Valencia, and Barcelona.
In 1938 Italian planes carried out most of the large-scale bombing operations, striking the cities of [[Bombing of Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Bombing of Alicante|Alicante]], [[Bombing of Granollers|Granollers]], and [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]], as well as the railway stations of [[Bombing of Sant Vicenç de Calders|Sant Vicenç de Calders]] in 1938 and [[Bombing of Xàtiva|Xàtiva]] in 1939. With a total of 728 raids on Spanish Mediterranean cities, the ''Aviazione Legionaria'' dropped 16,558 bombs and inflicted numerous casualties.<ref name="heiberg20042">Heiberg, Morte (2004). ''Emperadores del Mediterráneo: Franco, Mussolini y la guerra civil española.'' Barcelona: Crítica. {{ISBN|8484324702}}; p. 133</ref> By the end of the conflict the ''Aviazione Legionaria'' had logged a total of 135,265 hours' flying time on 5,318 operations, dropping 11,524 tons of bombs and destroying 943 enemy air units and 224 ships.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Balfour |first1=Sebastian |last2=Preston |first2=Paul |year=2009 |title=Spain and the great powers in the twentieth century |location=London, UK; New York, USA |publisher=Routledge. |page=172 |isbn=978-0-415-18078-8}}</ref> In total, Italy provided the Nationalists with 660 planes, 150 tanks, 800 artillery pieces, 10,000 machine guns, and 240,000 rifles.<ref>Thomas (2001). pp. 938–939.</ref>
